5|$|In {{keeping with}} their history, the Churches of Christ claim the <b>New</b> <b>Testament</b> as their sole rule {{of faith and}} {{practice}} in deciding matters of doctrine and ecclesiastical structure. They view the Old Testament as divinely inspired and historically accurate, {{but they do not}} consider its laws to be binding under the New Covenant in Christ (unless they are repeated in the <b>New</b> <b>Testament)</b> (Hebrews 8: 7-13). They believe that the <b>New</b> <b>Testament</b> demonstrates how a person may become a Christian (and thus a part of the universal Church of Christ) and how a church should be collectively organized and carry out its scriptural purposes.|$|E
